PLEASE READ IF YOU HAVE GLITCHES STREAMING SPOTIFY ON Apple Watch WITH THE Nike Run Club app

Praying this gets acknowledged because its a serious problem I AND OTHERS have experienced while running with the Apple Watch (I'm series 4 but my friend had series 5) streaming spotify. before you skip I've been working with and sending logs to a team at nike (who are doing a great job staying in contact) and it seems that streaming spotify while using the NRC app causes frequent crashes. I'll leave at 85% battery and stream Spotify, watch dies 30 mins in, comes back on for a minute, and dies until I charge it at home. Then after 10 mins on the charger it goes from 65% to 75%?? not sure if this is a "spotify issue" but I've gone on runs with downloaded MP3's with no issue, have 80% battery capacity on my watch health, and no issues streaming Apple Music in the past.

Pretty disappointed apple hasn't fixed this since they sell a Nike Apple Watch with the Run Club App LITERALLY pre-installed. I'll try Apple Music again for a month and see if it "solves the issue". I'll keep you all updated. I've checked plenty of forums and others have experienced the same issue. thank you for reading this, thumbs up to spread the word!!

I‚Äôve never had a smartwatch at all, but a man wears his watch on its left wrist despite the saying that you can wear it where you want or that the correct placement is the opposite of your dominant hand. Just think of the placement of the crown wheel, it‚Äôs supposed to be facing outwards, so that your other hand can access it. Having the watch on your right, puts the crown wheel on the inside, and you‚Äôd have to twist your left hand awkwardly to access it.

So, a watch is to be on the left wrist. (There might/should be options with the crown on the other side for left handed people, like there are inverted guitars, but I‚Äôm not aware of it).

To see why I‚Äôm right... check a photo of Obama, he‚Äôs left-handed but still he wears the watch on his left wrist correctly.

Can someone answer my question? Can you stream music via the watch WITHOUT having the cellular model?

I got you, recently purchased a Wifi only Apple watch for this reason. Without Cellular you CAN listen via bluetooth to music or podcasts you've downloaded while connected to Wifi, but not from any popular hosts with the exeption of Apple. The question of compatibility now shifts to the question of which streaming service do you use. IF you get everything from Apple Music/Podcasts then youre set. Downloads and bluetooth listening are no problem. But spotify notably does NOT allow bluetooth listening unless you have a phone in the vicinity, because it does not support downloads. Strangely enough the only 3rd party service that I've seen allowing downloads is Pandora Premium...likely due to the lack of real competition to Apple Music. That's the best i've got friend, good luck.

As for Sleep, I've been using an app combo of Smart Alarm (for the Watch) and SleepMatic (for tracking on the phone). I suspect that it's better than the new Sleep because basically I set the latest time when I need to be up and Smart Alarm picks a moment within a 30-minute range before that time, when I'm the most ready to wake up, so that it's more natural. I love the channel.  But... I disagree with your assessment of the battery and I‚Äôm not sure why others aren‚Äôt talking more about it.  It‚Äôs a huge improvement from my Series 4.  I used to run 13mi with my Series 4 with all sensors active and music.  I would start with a full charge and would have 35% at completion.  After receiving my Series 6 I ran a 17mi run with all sensors active and music playing.  I started with a full charge and had 55% at completion.  So I went further, had even more sensors running with an always on display and had significantly more battery remaining after completion.  Here‚Äôs the real life impact.  Based on those results, the Series 6 would make it through a full Marathon.  The Series 4, would not.  It‚Äôs not very scientific but it‚Äôs the single biggest reason I am glad I upgraded.  Oh... The other big difference.  The GPS map plotting is far more accurate.  It doesn‚Äôt cut through or round off the corners the way the Series 4 did.

Now, here is the counter review in short order: I'm 55 years old with several comorbidities. I have had a major heart attack, some respiratory issues, and a mini-stroke when I was 39 years old. I am doing very well now, but it was a hard road. While for someone around your age and relatively good health these new health features on the Apple Watch (which are not new in the marketplace), it is a godsend. Yes, it's not completely accurate in all things, but to have multiple ways to track several measurements that at least gives someone like me with my health issues a good IDEA of where we are ‚Äî including fall detection and the other features in earlier updates ‚Äî the peace of mind ALONE eases significant stress. Which is good for your health. Which makes it worth the extra few hundred dollars. I do NOT want a half a dozen gadgets to keep up with, no matter how much less expensive they are, unless it is merely to have them on standby for more accurate readings if need them. Having a singular device that gives me REASONABLE confidence in the technology? Absolutely. So, is the Apple Watch 6 worth it for people who don't need those features? Probably not. But don't sort of passively dismiss the millions of people for whom these features may not be perfect, but they are damn sure worth the extra price.

He is a visually impaired and building an App named as Louie Voice Control that allows a user to do everything within his phone with just voice commands. None of the big names like Google Assistant, Alexa, Siri can do everything that Louie does. These Voice Assistants tend to be superficial & will allow a user to do only 2-3 things within an App. Louie in comparison will fully voice control an App - each and every feature within the App. Also Voice Assistants or Personal Assistants have a nasty habit of going silent every now and then. Louie in comparison does a two-way continuous interaction ‚Äì just like a human interaction with the user.


In short, Louie is an accessibility App and can be used by all voice-lovers including but not limited to visually impaired, blind, motor-disabled, elderly, people with limited manual dexterity and all hands-free lovers.

Love your channel and I often resonate with your takes on products. But I think the Series 6 Watch, even for some Series 5 owners, can represent a substantive jump in value and performance. Let me explain.

The quick charging capability of the Series 6 is not a small improvement. I believe it's a big step up, especially for those who use their Apple Watch for sleep tracking. The Series 6 can accept a full charge in 1.5 hours. The Series 4 and 5 and the SE take 2.5 hours. For me, that's the difference between being able to fully charge my Watch in the morning as I prepare for work and not being able to get a full charge. Also, the Series 6 has a 5Ghz WiFi radio in addition to 2.4Ghz. The Series 4 and 5 and SE only have 2.4Ghz. That can represent a substantive level of improvement when downloading rich content to the watch. The Series 6 is also the only Apple Watch with the U1 proximity chip which will likely offer upcoming functionalities previous watches won‚Äôt. The Series 6 also has a noticably brighter and easier to see display when in its always-on mode IN BRIGHT OUTDOOR LIGHT. These are not very sexy features to talk about. But with regards to day in and day out use of the Watch, I think they need to be considered when making a decision about which Watch to buy.

The blood oxygen thing on the watch actually would have been extremely helpful when my lung collapsed a couple years ago. My lung first collapsed partially (which hurt like hell), then the doctors sent me home because my lung wasn't collapsing anymore. I told my mom, they took me to the hospital and it turns out my lung had fully collapsed. I did not feel that full collapse. If I had the blood oxygen test conveniently on my wrist, I wouldn't have come close to writing it off. I wouldn't write something like that off as "bells and whistles".
Edit: I know its a very particular situation but it could still save lives

Is it just me or am I too old for this? Why would I want a watch that constantly buzzes when I get a notification? Sure, you can turn that off. But then what's the point of the thing? It can read my blood oxygen levels, neat. But not professionally so. Useless. It can detect my heartbeat. Neat... for when I'm working out. Then it's a watch that cannot be upgraded and will be trash in a few years. Granted, it's Apple, so it'll have a 5 or 6-year lifespan. But still, it'll become trash in a few years. Oh yes, it can show the time. I don't care about the time being on my wrist. It's on my phone and on my laptop and on my PC and pretty much everywhere I need one (public transport) there are clocks all over the place.

I'd like to want an Apple Watch, but I'd fail to see a useful application for it in daily life. If only it came with a fingerprint scanner built-in, then it could unlock my MBP instead of having to always open the lid to access that feature. Oh, also: APPLE!
